			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				There is one point which i think should be made;<BR>
much more important than which race you chose or which stats you put your starting points into, is HOW you play your character, knowing your limits, the limits of the group and the zone you are in. And the most important rule above all: you, as the tank, should ALWAYS be the last group member to run, unless you can keep all mobs agroed on you and lead them away from the group.<BR>
<BR>
Strength is nice, but warriors are NOT damage dealers, however there are plenty of +str items out there if you want them at later levels.<BR>
<BR>
Stamina is not really important, in a good group a mob wont usually last long enough for you to run out of stamina, and even if it does most casters have an invigorate spell to refresh stamina and is fairly low level so can be memed and cast in a matter of seconds.<BR>
<BR>
Agility should be atleast 85-90 or so to be effective, any less is probably not a good idea, and more is wasted.<BR>
<BR>
Dexterity only affects how offen you crit or cripp, do not worry about it too much. The extra damage from the occasional crit is not worth spending points, they would be better used in str where the extra 4 or 5 dmg per hit would be better than more crits in the long run.<BR>
<BR>
Wis, Int and Cha have basically no effect on a warrior at all.<BR>
<BR>
One other note, if you do manage to get str, sta(?), agi or dex to very high levels, around 180+ there is a noticable increase in their effects. Try getting Dex up to 150 unbuffed, then a shaman buff etc. 210+ dex does make for alot of crits however still more for effect than anything.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
