	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				One thing people need to be aware of, and this is straight from the guys at Verant.<BR>
Okay, more than one thing.<BR>
1) Str influences maximum and avergae damage. The higher it is, the higher (slightly) they are. It also directly impacts how much you can carry. This is helpful, but not particularly crucial. Str makes a difference, but at high levels it's not really all the big a deal to hit for 95 instead of 90 while the wizard behind you Ice Comets for 1000 =).<BR>
2) Agility affects a number of different skills. First, it adds a small amount of ac directly to your total. Howeverm this amount usually varied by only about 20-30 points from an agi of 75 to an agi of 105. However, AGILITY ALSO ADDS SOMEWHAT TO THE AC OF EACH PIECE OF ARMOR YOU EQUIP. Try it sometime. Make a char with 100 agi, then the same race (I tried barbarian) with only 80. Get yourself a piece of armor and do an ac before-and-after with each character trying the same piece of armor. You will notice a difference. The higher the base ac of the armor, the more noticable to effect of high agility. However, agi over about 100 isn't overly effective, so don't worry about it.<BR>
3) DEX does NOT, I don't care what you think, affect chance to hit. That is based purely on weapon skill and mob AC. What DEX does affect is the rate of PROCS. Directly. You wanna proc those twin ykeshas you bought a lot, better have DEX up in the 90's or 100's. It also affects the rate of rise of certain combat skills, I.E. dual wield or double attack, as well as most of the rogue-specific skills like backstab and pickpocket. Once again--DEX does NOT affect your chance to hit. Period. It also affects a caster's ability to succesfully cast after being interrupted--good, but in a good group you really shouldn't be getting interrupted anyhow.<BR>
4) Stamina affects your fatigue meter--higher means you get tired slower. It also affects how long you hold your breath, and -- most important for warriors -- your max hp. However, the difference between a lv 40 barbarian with 120 stm and one with 105 stm is around 150-200 HP. When the mob double attacks for 90, there isn't much of that left. AC is king for fighters even more than HP--get good armor.<BR>
5) INT governs mana supply, as any good (pure) caster knows. Wizzies, mages, necros, and enchanters, as well as shadow knights, should pay special attention to this. the first four classes especially should think about maxing this skill--although enchanters have to worry about charisma too. It also governs the rate at which most skills are learned. For warriors, unless you plan on taking up a trade skill -- don't reccomend that -- you don't need this. Your skills'll go up just fine through normal fighting--trust me. Even dumb ogres can get their skills up without much trouble.<BR>
I'd write more, but WIS and CHA are more or less useless to warriors, so I'll spare you the details. Again, this is STRAIGHT FROM VERANT, so it ought to be correct. Hope this helps.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
